---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'schengen-requirements', text: 'Schengen Visa Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'coverage-minimums', text: 'Minimum Coverage Standards', level: 2 },
  { id: 'documentation', text: 'Documentation for Visa', level: 2 },
  { id: 'long-stay-options', text: 'Long-Stay Visa Coverage', level: 2 },
  { id: 'common-mistakes', text: 'Common Mistakes to Avoid', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Europe Insurance Options', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Short-Term Coverage', href: '/best/short-term-insurance' },
  { title: 'Au Pair Insurance', href: '/best/au-pair-insurance' },
  { title: 'Visa Insurance Requirements', href: '/guides/visa-requirements-health-insurance' },
  { title: 'Student Insurance', href: '/best/student-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'schengenApproved', header: 'Schengen Approved' },
  { key: 'coverage', header: 'Coverage Amount' },
  { key: 'documentation', header: 'Visa Letter' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  {
    provider: 'AXA Schengen',
    schengenApproved: 'Specifically designed',
    coverage: '€30,000+',
    documentation: 'Instant letter',
    price: '€0.99/day',
  },
  {
    provider: 'Allianz Travel',
    schengenApproved: 'Meets requirements',
    coverage: '€30,000+',
    documentation: 'Available',
    price: '€1.50/day',
  },
  {
    provider: 'DR-WALTER',
    schengenApproved: 'EU specialist',
    coverage: '€30,000+',
    documentation: 'Visa letter included',
    price: '€1.20/day',
  },
  {
    provider: 'Europ Assistance',
    schengenApproved: 'European focus',
    coverage: '€30,000+',
    documentation: 'Instant documentation',
    price: '€1.30/day',
  },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Schengen Visa Insurance 2026 | EU Travel Coverage Requirements"
  description="Insurance meeting Schengen visa requirements. Coverage for European travel with €30,000 minimum, repatriation, and visa-compliant documentation."
  headline="Best Schengen Visa Insurance"
  subheadline="Schengen visas require specific insurance coverage. Without the right policy and documentation, your visa application gets rejected. Here's how to meet the requirements correctly."
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get a Quote"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/axa"
>
  <p class="text-lg mb-8">
    Schengen visa insurance isn't optional—it's required. Your application needs proof of coverage meeting specific standards: €30,000 minimum, repatriation coverage, valid throughout the Schengen area. Getting this wrong delays or denies your visa. Here's how to get it right.
  </p>

  <h2 id="top-picks" class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Our Top Picks for Schengen Visa Insurance</h2>

  <p class="mb-4">
    These providers specialize in Schengen visa compliance. They provide instant documentation, meet all requirements, and are widely accepted by European consulates.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">AXA Schengen — Best Dedicated Option</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The good:</strong> AXA Schengen is specifically designed for Schengen visa requirements. Instant documentation after purchase. Explicitly meets all EU requirements. Very affordable—starting under €1/day. Widely recognized by consulates. Simple online purchase process.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Basic coverage—meets requirements but isn't premium insurance. For visa compliance, not comprehensive health needs. If you want better coverage, consider upgrading beyond minimum requirements.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Short-term Schengen visa applicants who need simple, compliant, affordable coverage.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Allianz Travel — Best Known Brand</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The good:</strong> Allianz is globally recognized and trusted by consulates. Their Schengen-compliant plans meet all requirements. Good claim handling reputation. Available for various trip lengths. Some plans offer more coverage than minimum requirements.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Slightly more expensive than budget-focused Schengen insurers. You're paying for brand recognition. For basic visa compliance, cheaper options work equally well.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Travelers who prefer a well-known international insurance brand.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">DR-WALTER — Best for Extended Stays</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The good:</strong> DR-WALTER specializes in European travel insurance. Their PROVISIT plans work for Schengen visas. Good for longer stays, not just short trips. German company with strong European knowledge. Visa documentation included. Also works for student and au pair visas.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The limits:</strong> European focus may mean less recognition outside EU. Website and service primarily German-oriented. Better for extended European travel than brief trips.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Travelers planning extended stays in the Schengen area or applying for longer-term visas.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Europ Assistance — Best European Option</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The good:</strong> Europ Assistance is a major European insurer with strong Schengen expertise. Instant documentation available. Good coverage options from basic to comprehensive. European presence means good claims handling within Schengen. Multi-language support.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>The limits:</strong> Not as focused on Schengen specifically as AXA Schengen product. May be more complex to navigate than dedicated Schengen products. Pricing varies by coverage level.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-6">
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Travelers who want European expertise with flexibility in coverage levels.
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <CTABox
    title="Applying for a Schengen Visa?"
    description="Get compliant insurance with instant documentation. Don't risk visa rejection for wrong coverage."
    buttonText="Get Schengen Insurance"
    buttonHref="/go/axa"
  />

  <h2 id="schengen-requirements" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Schengen Visa Requirements</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">What is Schengen Insurance?</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Schengen area countries (most EU plus Norway, Switzerland, Iceland, Liechtenstein) require visitors to have health insurance as a visa condition. This protects both travelers and European healthcare systems. Without compliant insurance, your visa application is incomplete.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Legal Requirements</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    EU Regulation 810/2009 establishes Schengen visa insurance requirements. All short-stay visa applicants must have insurance covering the entire Schengen area, lasting the entire stay, meeting coverage minimums, and including repatriation. This isn't optional guidance—it's legally required.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Who Needs Schengen Insurance</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Citizens of countries requiring Schengen visas need this insurance for their visa application. Visa-exempt travelers (US, Canadian, Australian, etc.) don't legally need it for short visits, but having travel insurance is still strongly recommended. Long-stay visa requirements vary by country.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">When to Purchase</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Buy insurance before your visa appointment. You need to submit proof of insurance with your visa application. Purchase should cover your planned travel dates—from entry to exit. You can buy online and receive documentation instantly from most Schengen insurance providers.
  </p>

  <h2 id="coverage-minimums" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Minimum Coverage Standards</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">€30,000 Minimum Coverage</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Coverage must be at least €30,000 for medical expenses. This covers hospitalization, emergency care, and treatment costs. Most Schengen-specific policies meet or exceed this. Check that your policy explicitly shows €30,000+ coverage for visa documentation.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Repatriation Coverage</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Insurance must cover repatriation for medical reasons—transport back to your home country if medically necessary. This is separate from medical treatment coverage. Schengen-compliant policies include repatriation. Verify this is explicitly mentioned in your policy.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Urgent Medical Treatment</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Emergency medical treatment must be covered. This includes emergency hospital care, urgent surgery, and immediate medical needs. Routine care isn't required—this is about emergencies and urgent situations.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Geographic Coverage</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Coverage must be valid throughout the entire Schengen area—all 27 member states. A policy covering only France doesn't meet requirements if you might enter through Germany. Schengen-specific policies automatically cover the entire area.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Duration Coverage</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Insurance must cover your entire stay plus any grace period. If your visa is for 15 days, insurance should cover at least those 15 days. Some consulates recommend coverage exceeding your planned stay by a few days for travel delays.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Need Compliant Coverage?"
    description="Get insurance that meets all Schengen requirements with instant documentation."
    buttonText="Get Compliant Insurance"
    buttonHref="/go/axa"
  />

  <h2 id="documentation" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Documentation for Visa</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Insurance Certificate</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    You need an insurance certificate showing: your name, coverage dates, coverage amount (€30,000+), geographic coverage (Schengen area), and that repatriation is included. Most Schengen insurers provide instant downloadable certificates after purchase. This document goes with your visa application.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">What Consulates Check</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Consulates verify: coverage meets minimums, dates match your travel plans, coverage includes all Schengen countries, the insurer is legitimate. Using a recognized Schengen insurance provider avoids scrutiny. Unknown insurers may require additional verification.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Rejection Reasons</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Common rejection reasons: coverage under €30,000, dates don't cover full stay, policy excludes Schengen countries, missing repatriation coverage, unrecognized insurer, or unclear documentation. Getting compliant insurance from the start avoids these problems.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Print vs. Digital Documentation</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Most consulates accept printed certificates. Some accept digital proof. Check your specific consulate's requirements. Having a printed copy is safest—even if digital is accepted, paper backup helps with any issues.
  </p>

  <h2 id="long-stay-options" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Long-Stay Visa Coverage</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Beyond 90 Days</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Standard Schengen visas allow 90 days per 180-day period. Longer stays require national long-stay visas (Type D), not Schengen visas. Insurance requirements for long-stay visas are set by individual countries, not Schengen-wide rules.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Country-Specific Long-Stay Requirements</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Germany, France, Spain, and other countries have their own long-stay visa insurance requirements. These often exceed Schengen minimums. Research your specific country's requirements. National visa offices specify insurance standards for their long-stay visas.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Student Visa Coverage</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Student visas in European countries require insurance meeting national standards. Coverage often needs to last the academic year. Some countries require public health enrollment alongside private insurance. Check your specific study destination's requirements.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Work Visa Coverage</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Work visas may include employment-based coverage or require private insurance. EU Blue Card and national work permits have varying requirements. Employers often provide coverage for work permit holders. Verify whether employer or personal coverage is expected.
  </p>

  <h2 id="common-mistakes" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Insufficient Coverage Amount</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Policies under €30,000 don't meet requirements—even €29,000 fails. Verify your policy explicitly shows €30,000+ coverage. Cheap travel insurance that doesn't meet minimums wastes money and delays your visa.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Wrong Dates</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Coverage dates must include your entire stay. If your visa is April 1-30, insurance covering April 1-25 fails. Buy coverage for your full trip. Consider extra days for potential travel delays.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Non-Schengen Insurance</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Generic travel insurance may not meet Schengen requirements or provide proper documentation. Using a Schengen-specific product guarantees compliance. Don't assume regular travel insurance qualifies.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Missing Repatriation</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Medical coverage alone isn't enough—repatriation must be explicitly included. Policies without repatriation coverage don't meet requirements. Verify repatriation is mentioned in your policy documentation.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Late Purchase</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Buying insurance after your visa appointment doesn't work—you need documentation for the application. Purchase before your consulate appointment. Instant online documentation makes this easy.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Get It Right the First Time"
    description="Don't risk visa rejection. Get insurance that meets all Schengen requirements with proper documentation."
    buttonText="Get Your Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/axa"
  />

  <h2 id="faqs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Is Schengen visa insurance really required?</h3>
      <p>Yes, legally required. EU regulations mandate health insurance for Schengen visa applicants. Without compliant insurance documentation, your visa application is incomplete and will be rejected. This isn't a recommendation—it's a legal requirement.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What's the minimum coverage needed?</h3>
      <p>€30,000 minimum for medical expenses, plus repatriation coverage, valid throughout all Schengen countries, for your entire stay. Most Schengen-specific insurance products meet or exceed these requirements. Verify coverage amount is shown on your documentation.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Can I use my regular travel insurance?</h3>
      <p>Maybe. Your travel insurance must meet all Schengen requirements and provide proper documentation. If it meets €30,000 coverage, includes repatriation, covers all Schengen countries, and you can get a proper certificate, it may work. Schengen-specific products guarantee compliance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">When should I buy the insurance?</h3>
      <p>Before your visa appointment. You need insurance documentation to submit with your visa application. Purchase online and receive instant documentation. Most Schengen insurers provide immediate downloadable certificates.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Does insurance guarantee visa approval?</h3>
      <p>No. Proper insurance is necessary but not sufficient for visa approval. You must meet all visa requirements—insurance is just one element. Proper insurance prevents rejection for that reason; other factors still affect approval.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">What if my travel dates change?</h3>
      <p>Contact your insurer about modifying coverage dates. Many Schengen insurance providers allow date changes. If you need to extend, purchase additional coverage before original coverage ends. Don't let coverage lapse during your stay.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mt-12">
    This information is for educational purposes. Schengen visa requirements are established by EU regulations. Verify current requirements with your specific consulate, as procedures may vary. Last updated: April 2026.
  </p>
</PageShell>
